Before starting: What you already need

Inside EC2:

Docker installed

Image exists

Check:

docker images

You should see:

myweb v1

Step 1: Create ECR repository

Go AWS Console:

Search:

ECR

Open:

Amazon Elastic Container Registry

Click:

Create repository

Repository name:

myweb

Visibility:

Choose:

Private

Create repository

After creation AWS gives repository URI like:

385105852201.dkr.ecr.eu-north-1.amazonaws.com/myweb

Important: save this URI.

Step 2: Login Docker to ECR

Inside EC2 run:

aws ecr get-login-password --region ap-south-1 | docker login --username AWS

--password-stdin your-repository-uri-without-/myweb

Example:

aws ecr get-login-password --region ap-south-1 | docker login --username AWS

--password-stdin 123456789012.dkr.ecr.ap-south-1.amazonaws.com

Explanation

aws ecr get-login-password

AWS generates temporary login password

docker login

Docker authenticates with ECR

--username AWS

Fixed username for ECR

If aws command fails

Install AWS CLI first:

sudo yum install aws-cli -y

Check:

aws --version

If AWS credentials not configured

Run:

aws configure

Enter:

● Access key

● Secret key

● region = ap-south-1

Step 3: Tag your image

Your current image:

myweb:v1

ECR requires full repository name.

Run:

docker tag myweb:v1 your-full-ecr-uri:latest

Example:

docker tag myweb:v1 123456789012.dkr.ecr.ap-south-1.amazonaws.com/myweb:latest

Explanation

Why tagging?

Because Docker must know destination registry.

Step 4: Push image

Run:

docker push your-full-ecr-uri:latest

Example:

docker push 123456789012.dkr.ecr.ap-south-1.amazonaws.com/myweb:latest

What happens now?

Docker uploads layers one by one.

You will see:

layer already exists

pushed

Step 5: Verify in AWS Console

Refresh ECR repository.

You should see:

latest

Image uploaded successfully
